  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass (or formula mass) of ammonium (\\(NH_4^+\\)), you need to sum the atomic masses of all the atoms in the ion.\n\n1. Identify the elements and their quantities in the ammonium ion:\n   - Nitrogen (N): 1 atom\n   - Hydrogen (H): 4 atoms\n\n2. Find the atomic masses of these elements from the periodic table:\n   - Atomic mass of Nitrogen (N): approximately 14.01 amu (atomic mass units)\n   - Atomic mass of Hydrogen (H): approximately 1.01 amu\n\n3. Calculate the total molecular mass by multiplying the quantity of each element by its atomic mass and then summing those values:\n\n\\[ \\text{Molecular mass of NH}_4^+ = (1 \\times \\text{atomic mass of N}) + (4 \\times \\text{atomic mass of H}) \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Molecular mass of NH}_4^+ = (1 \\times 14.01 \\text{ amu}) + (4 \\times 1.01 \\text{ amu}) \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Molecular mass of NH}_4^+ = 14.01 \\text{ amu} + 4.04 \\text{ amu} \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Molecular mass of NH}_4^+ = 18.05 \\text{ amu} \\]\n\nSo, the molecular mass of the ammonium ion (\\(NH_4^+\\)) is approximately 18.05 amu.",
